y formed on the Continent; see   Turberville  .","perhaps in some cases a nickname from Old French and Middle English <i>turbot</i>, <i>turbut</i> ‘turbot’, for someone who caught or sold or resembled this fish."]},{"name":"Turbyfill","meanings":["Altered form of English   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Tuberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Turville","meanings":["English (Surrey and Hampshire; of Norman origin):","habitational name from Tourville‐la‐Campagne (Eure, France). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thórr</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ (from Latin <i>villa</i>).","occasionally a shortened form of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Turbeville","meanings":["English: variant of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Troublefield","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Turberville  ."]}]},{"name":"Hamon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Raimundo .   See  <b>Raymond</b>   ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hamon de Turburville was born about 1283, in Tythegston, Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Wilcock Turberville, was 15 and his mother, Mawd verch Hopkin, was 15. He had at least 1 son with Isabel de Penrees. He died in 1340, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"about 1283–1340":"umbes 1283–1340","1283–1340":"1283–1340","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1290–1345":"1290–1345","1310–1370":"1310–1370","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","about 1283":"umbes 1283","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Tythegston, Glamorgan, Wales":"Tythegston, Glamorgan, Wales","Tythegestone, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1283–1340":"noin 1283–1340","1283–1340":"1283–1340","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1290–1345":"1290–1345","1310–1370":"13